charity.description:
At Macmillan, we will move mountains to help people with cancer live life as fully as they can.

We’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can’t support everyone who needs us. To
donate, volunteer, raise money or campaign with us, call 0300 1000 200 or visit macmillan.org.uk
charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
On 31st July 2021, we will be (hopefully) completing the Dedham Vale Mighty Hike - a 26 mile hike through the countryside and villages of the Dedham Vale area - to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support. 

Macmillan support people with cancer and their families through the hardest times of their lives. In their words.. "If you’re diagnosed, your worries are our worries. We’re doing whatever it takes. But without your help we can’t support everyone who needs us."

Please support us however you can.. We will be arranging various fundraisers as soon as current restrictions allow!

Kate & Lucie x

story:
Get ready for some virtual fun by solving our mind-boggling mystery. Let's get together, solve a murder and raise money for people living with cancer.

We have set the fundraising target as £70, we thought we could each donate £10 (the price of 2 drinks or..... 1 London cocktail), hope that's ok with everybody. 

Don't forget to gift aid and when you donate they will say that JustGiving won't be charging a platform fee and they suggest you add a contribution to JustGiving - automatically set to 15% but you can change this to 10%, 5%, other (and specify how much you are willing to pay JustGiving for their services). 

Can't wait to see you all there!

Samuel has decided to challenge himself to a month of NO PS4! For an 8 year old this is a big challenge to set. 

Samuel decided that to make the challenge more worthwhile he wanted to fundraise. He chose MacMillan Cancer Support to donate his fundraising too. 

We have seen it on the news often that people have been unable to get the treatment they desperately need for a long time now due to COVID and we know that every penny really will help this charity support those in need. 

Thank you to everyone for their support.

Simon, Marie, Katrina and all the family

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page which we have created in Sheena's memory. Sheena will always be remembered  for her bravery, her sense of adventure , her friendship and above all her kindness and compassion. She will be a big loss to us all and our lives have been made better for having had her in them. 

A funeral service will be held for Sheena on Thursday the 4th March at 15:40 at Carlisle Crematorium. For those wishing to remember Sheena or make/send a contribution, the family asks, as per Sheena's wishes, that in lieu of flowers donations be sent to Macmillan Cancer Support. 

Our thoughts and love go out to all of Sheena's loved ones at this time.

story: Lee Kirton: On the 10th July 2021 at 8am, a group of friends and family made up of runners and cyclists will take part in a challenging safe event in their own location to raise money for Macmillan Cancer support. Even more awareness is important around Cancer and the effects it has on a lot of people and even more so during the Covid pandemic. Sadly we all have our loses and stories to tell and this is to honor them and help others fighting this horrible disease. Individuals will complete a 15k run or 100k cycle starting at 8am and share their pictures and completion time to help inspire others and complete a personal challenge raising much needed funds... Personal fitness challenges are needed also for mental health during a challenging time, so this benefits a lot of people who have recently started running or cycling, or literally want to train harder. Please support us all as motivation is needed. Taking part, a team of all ages - Lee Kirton, Andrew Minty, Barry Keating, Bren Kelly, Brian Simpson, Katy Simpson, Gordon Simpson, Jo Simpson, Claire Simpson, Archie Simpson, Duncan Purves, Jonathan Chambers, Laurence Bray, Mark Croxon, Mark Hughes, Simon Barratt, Simon Maxwell, Paul (Spike) Murrells, Tony Hinton, Jim Kench, Elle Kench, Mia Kench, Tom Wallace, Alison Beasley, Jake Mattock, Alvin Hussey, Reda Asakaviciute, Jorge Sanchez and Cat Channon. Thank you to everyone giving it a go and thanks to everyone putting in their hard-earned pennies x

charity.name: St John Ambulance
eventName: 100km per week exercise bike challenge for St John's Ambulance
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This year I am doing my Bronze Duke of Edinburgh and I decided to set myself a fundraising challenge to raise money for St John's ambulance. I have chosen to do cycling because during this lockdown I have tried to get fitter and have a better mental health than last lockdown and inspire people to get up and moving during tough times.  MY challenge is to do 100km on my bike each week for 12 weeks. 100km is about 4 and a half hours for me spread out during the week so it is a real challenge but I am determined to complete it. I start on Monday 22nd February and finish on Monday 17th May. 

St John's ambulance is an amazing charity. They offer training courses, advice, volunteering opportunities, event support, products and more to help the public when they become ill or injured. They do an unbelievable job and rely on volunteers to work for them and they can only help thanks to donations.During Covid-19 they have been training vaccine volunteers who ultimately will get us all back to normal life. As you probably know, the NHS is under lots of pressure at the moment and St John's relieve some of that pressure by helping all thanks to volunteers. St John's ambulance do an amazing job and if you are unfortunate enough to become ill or injured they will be there to help. 

I hope you are generous enough to dig deep and donate to help this wonderful charity keep everyone healthy and well during this tough time and help us recover from Covid-19.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. Two of my grandparents died in recent from heart complications which is why I’ve decided to support this charity.

During Covid times charities are having a really tough time fundraising and so I wanted to do something to help. I’m probably going to use this page for a few different fundraising things. First off I need to clear some stuff out at home! Usually I’d take stuff to charities shops but that’s a bit tricky at the moment, plus some people would really benefit from the donations. So I’m offering the option to donate to this fundraising page if you’re able.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
British Heart foundation
This year will be my 60th birthday, to mark the start of my 6th decade I am planning to attempt to run , walk or swim the Grand Canyon Virtual Challenge . It will take me 280 miles (451 km) along The Colorado River , I'll be doing this to raise money for the British Heart foundation.  I feel very lucky to get this far in life as most of my family are no longer with us. This will be in memory of my Mum, Dad and my Sister who was only 55 when she died , all heart related deaths . Then to rub salt in the wounds my niece's son was born with a hole in his heart to continue the jinx.

It has been a rough time for a lot of charities, this is why I want do something to help the British Heart foundation.

I have set up a just giving page for any donations you may be able to spare as every little will help. I'm hoping I can reach £250 .

                                  Thank you so much for reading my post and if you do have any penny's to spare it will go to good use.'m collecting vital funds for the British HWell done eart Foundation, to power pioneering research into heart and cardiovascular diseases. The money we raise will help beat heartbreak forever.

story:
Anthony Williams and Peter Edwards are sadly no longer with us as they both lost their lives in the past twelve months. Something that has rocked us all, as a team we felt the least we could do is raise money for a charity closest to them in their name. 

The challenge is to run from lands end to John O Groats twice, there and back again - (unlike Frodo and Sam we won’t have Gollum dragging us along, but we will be doing this as a team)

The aim is to get this challenge done in six weeks time with a total of 2841km to hit.

Thank you for all the donations that will come I know they would both appreciate it, although would come with a side of moaning about something 😂. Both great guys and truly were the heart of the club!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
On February 29th 2020 we lost my dad, Neil, after he had a sudden heart attack. Unfortunately as we went into lockdown right before his funeral, we were unable to celebrate his life in the way that we wanted. We had hoped that by the anniversary we would be able to hold a memorial service, but with that being unable to go ahead as well this seemed the perfect way to honour his memory.

My dad was the kindest, most loving and most hard working man and I was lucky to have him as my dad. He was quiet and introverted in public, and we would sometimes tease him for his lack of social skills! But he was never afraid of showing his family that he loved them.  After a tough year for everyone I hope that we are continuing to make him proud. 

It means a lot for you to consider donating to British Heart Foundation in my dad's memory. They are an amazing charity and with donations I hope that in the future no other family will have to suffer a sudden loss of a family member like we have.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I do this yearly so many people might be bored of my spiel by now but I think it's really important, so I'm going to keep on going! Many of us have been without family this year, friends and even just the weirdo down the street, I bet you even miss them now too but let's not make that a forever thing. Maybe someone has a heart issue that, with or without COVID, is life-threatening, maybe it just happens randomly and without warning. We all know now how hard it is to not have your loved ones and friends around you, despite what you or they are going through, so let's try to lessen that burden for many people. Let's fight heart disease and heart issues, more research, more knowledge, more scientists, more jobs and more awareness. KNOWLEDGE IS POWER, unfortunately MONEY BUYS KNOWLEDGE in come cases.

I'm giving up everything sweet in order to make a difference, that means no vodka cokes or a cheeky gin and lemonade, no Haribo or Twirls or even a Freddo. NOPE. Because I want you and everyone else to LOVE and BE LOVED by your friends and family. And do to that, people need to LIVE and research must be done.

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I've signed up to Dechox for the British Heart Foundation and I will give up cakes, biscuits, as well as sweets, chocolate and fizzy drinks for the whole of March, yes that is 31 days!!!

This challenge is about changing the world for people affected by heart and circulatory diseases.   

The pandemic is the biggest challenge the British Heart Foundation have faced in their 60 year history. And it's led to them being forced to make the devastating decision to cut their 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, they have never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help them keep up the pace of progress. My willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need them most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Please sponsor me in my challenge and help raise vital funds to support this great cause and help people affected by heart diseases.

Thank you x

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Ooh hello, how ya doing?

How am I? Good thanks, but ask me in March when I won't be having any chocolate for that month!!

I felt like I should be doing something worthwhile, so giving up chocolate will be a challenge for me.

I am raising money for the British Heart Foundation as that is, quite literally, close to my heart ❤️ 

So if you are able to give a little chunk of money, or a great big slab (obsessed with chocolate), that would be blooming marvellous, but hey no worries if not, I know times are hard at the moment.

And now for the info that I didn't write - "The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!"

Thank you from the bottom of my chocolate bar 🍫 x

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
My willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. My grandad 'dadar' out of nowhere had a heart attack and was very close to death a few years ago and now lives with a rare heart condition, it's not until something significant happens in your life that it makes you sit back and realise the damage you're doing to your body, and how quickly everything can end! During lockdown I've realised I need to start doing more, and I've decided to try and push myself out of my comfort zone and start doing challenging things for charity! I would really appreciate any donations if people can, just to give a little to one of many amazing charities because you never know when you might need their help!

SO NO CHOCOLATE FOR ME FOR 28 DAYS...LETS DO THIS!!! 

As my dadar will most probably say... "no chocolate for chunk"

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Why Dechox?

Well as many know, I love nothing more than a hot chocolate or good few squares (who am I kidding, bars) of chocolate. However, I have decided alongside my mum to go without for a whole month. I am taking on the challenge to give up chocolate(in all forms), sweets and fizzy drinks. 

This is madness I know, in fact I can’t quite believe it myself but I am doing it for a very good cause. Please help me through it by donating what you can, for the charity but also to save my waist line too! 


Unfortunately, heart and circulatory diseases still kill 1 in 4 in the UK, which is an extremely high number. The British Heart foundation do such great things to create awareness and support many families, so please help me with this challenge. 

Lots of love, 

Jazz x

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: March 2013 I celebrated my 50th Birthday, 42 days after the celebrations I had a heart attack resulting in a stent fitted.                                                   Why ?                                                                                                        I had never smoked, rarely drank alcohol, I wasn’t excessively overweight and I followed a low fat diet majority of the time.                                                                                           So again, Why ?                                                                                 2018 a further 2 blockages were  found, resulting in 2 more stents fitted.                                                                                                                To this day I still have not found out why, the only possible answer was stress. So many people live stressful lives , totally oblivious to what it may be doing to your heart. We tend to focus on what we look like on the outside and don’t give a thought to our internal organs .                                         In this generation of technology many people are lacking in physical exercise also. We need to look after our ❤️ more than ever, otherwise it won’t be able to keep going for us. Please donate to help further research into cardiac related events.           Thank you xx

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
'He's had a heart attack' are words I never want to read in a message again. The person is fit, and super health conscious, so if it can happen to them, then it can happen to any of us. We all take our bodies for granted and assume it is working just fine. This has really made me think of the 'what ifs'.

If you know me well, you know I love my chocolate and my coke-a-cola. They are tough things to give up but not as tough as giving up on my heart. With my birthday looming too, this will be a challenge, but I am going for it - heart first! ❤

Please donate to this wonderful charity so families can be supported in everyday and every way.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

I am raising money in memory of my big brother Michael who was taken away too soon, 7 years ago in April. He was fit and healthy, yet his heart gave in. We forget that our hearts matter, and like many, I've eaten the goodies over this pandemic, and now I need to turn that around. For anyone that knows me, I'm a chocoholic, so stopping chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks throughout March is going to be pretty tough.

Your donations are important to keep me motivated, and to help the work that British heart Foundation do. I usually donate to shops when I have a sort out, but with shops closed due to the pandemic, this is my only way to help. 

Thank you for your support.

Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
My cousin Nicola and I are giving up chocolate for the whole of March, a de-chox! We are both big chocoholics but we’re doing this to raise money for the British Heart Foundation in support of my baby boy Oliver and all the other little heart warriors out there. Oliver was born with Coarctation of the aorta, he underwent life saving heart surgery at 3 days old to repair his narrow blood vessel. Our brave boy also has a biscuspid aortic valve and at 6 months old has just been diagnosed with an Atrial Septal Defect, a hole in his heart which he will likely need further intervention for when he’s a little older.

Congenital Heart Disease affects 1 in 100 babies, we want to raise as much as we can so research can continue to save all the special heart warriors ❤️

story: If anyone knows me, they will know this will be impossible for me to complete! March is also a very busy month, lots of birthdays and mothers day! I must be crazy, but chocolates will still be around in April Right!!! This is for a great cause and I'm up for the challenge! After experiencing gestational diabetes in pregnancy and having PCOS, I am always borderline diabetic, so may not be a bad habit to get out of my life! If you can spare anything to get me going through March that will be well worth the torture of the challenge 😀. Thank you for taking the time to read this and in advance thank you for your donation. Love from me x

story:
March will mark the 8th year of my life saving heart surgery. This year will also mark the 39th year of my brothers life saving heart surgery. Imagine seeing both of your children having to go through open heart surgery! (Sorry mum & Dad!) 

We, as a family are forever grateful to the BHF for all the research and for making these types of surgery possible. For saving so many lives every.single.year. 

This year, my youngest daughter wants to join us in this challenge (she is the biggest sugar fiend there is!!) so if you have a spare £1 or 2, please sponsor all 3 of us to raise money for this amazing charity. Thank you :)

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. story:
I'm already working on a healthier me and weight loss journey. 

I am a massive chocoholic. I have a real problem with chocolate as it's my trigger food. I'm embarrassed to admit at Christmas, hubby and I ate an entire tin of Cadbury heros in one evening watching a movie. Family size bar? Gone within an hour. Once I start I just cannot stop. 

So I'm challenging myself to give it up completely. Not just for March but for the whole of lent which also includes 2 weeks of February and a week of April. This might seem tame but in this pandemic, working as a nurse, with a young family and trying to study for a masters degree...chocolate is probably my only treat! It's meant to be a sacrifice so:

Lets do this for the BHF!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I'm giving up chocolate, sweets, cakes, biscuits and fizzy drinks. Basically everything tasty! Its going to be very hard because I have massive massive tooth and I prefer anything sweet to savoury. 

Please support me and donate to this brilliant cause. Anything will be gratefully received, small or large!

"The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now."

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
My granddad, as well as many other amazing men on my fathers, sadly passed away, suddenly, due to issues relating to their hearts. There are soooo many people out there living today that could be dead tomorrow because of heart failure and they don’t know what’s around the corner so...

We

Need

To

Make

A

Change

Now !

Help me and thousands of others in either taking part in the Dechox this March or donating to my fundraiser to keep me motivated as I really want to be able to do this! I looove sugar so this will be a massive change for me and I want to experience it. I’m hoping it does me a world of good and I’m able to lay off of the sugar a lot longer than just a month. I need to focus on my own heart and think about my future. I’m a sufferer of PCOS (Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome) which not only increases my chance of diabetes in the future but also of a heart disease too, due to being overweight.

Hopefully I can inspire others to join in too!

So I’m asking for your help to donate and keep me motivated to not linger towards the chocolate aisle in the shops!

I’ll keep you all up to date on the experience!

Thank you in advance :)

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. This may not seem a lot for someone to do give up chocolate for a month, for me it’s a huge challenge I was born with a heart and lung condition and last year was told my only possible future option will be a heart and lung transplant , I can’t run a marathon so please help me to support this cause the best way I can ❤️,  I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: I'm giving up chocolate and sweets for March 2021. This is to raise money for the British Heart Foundation. I lost my Step-dad in January to a combination of heart and kidney problems so wanted to do something to help raise funds for further research in these areas.
title: Emalene's Dechox Fundraising Page
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Ivor Evans
Name: Emalene's Dechox Fundraising Page

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Everyone who knows me, knows just how much I loooove chocolate! So this is going to be a massive challenge for me! Giving up chocolate for 31 days in March! I'd love to see your encouragement and support to keep me going throughout the whole of March! Thank you 😊 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
I’m Isaac and I am 10 years old. During lockdown I’ve been learning a lot of new things. I’ve learned about people with sight loss and the huge difference it makes for someone to have a guide dog. 

Did you know that every hour in the UK another person goes blind? Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss and 180,000 people with sight loss rarely leave home alone.

I am excited for lockdown to end so I can get out and about again with other people, but can you imagine lockdown ending and still being stuck at home because of sight loss and the fear of going out alone? Being alone and scared is horrible. 

A guide dog can change everything and help someone have a brilliant independent life. 

I’m going to do two thousand sit ups in one week (ouch!!) to raise as much money as I can to help people get guide dogs. Please help me to reach my target!! 😀

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

eventName: The Ring Road - around Iceland virtually!
story:
As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.

It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. 

By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

story:
Hello, and thank you for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am getting ready to cross the finish line in the Royal Parks Half Marathon raising money for the Guide Dogs for the Blind Association (Guide Dogs UK) on 10th October 2021. 

The dedication and care that goes into training a guide dog is so inspiring and truly commendable. Not only man's best friend, these wonderful animals give blind or partially sighted individuals the independence that most of us take for granted.

Aiming to raise £1,000 for Guide Dogs, I will run 13.1 miles (21k) after months of training and preparation. All the money I raise will help the charity provide more four legged heroes and other services to people who are blind or partially sighted, giving them life-changing freedom, mobility and independence.

Every hour, another person in the UK goes blind. When someone loses their sight, Guide Dogs is there to make sure they don’t lose their freedom as well.

I would love to reach my target of at least £1,000 for this amazing cause and would love your help in doing so. All donations, big or small, would be greatly appreciated.


  • £5 can support a working guide dog for a day
  • £25 can buy a white harness, the iconic symbol of a fully qualified guide dog
  • £95 can buy a Training School Kit for a guide dog trainer who teach pups the specialist skills they will need to become a qualified guide dog.
  • £140 can buy a Starter Kit for a new guide dog owner containing everything they need to start a life with their new guide dog. 

About Guide Dogs
The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.

www.guidedogs.org.uk

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

story:
Rather than giving something up for lent, I’ve decided on something else. 

I have set myself the challenge of exercising every day for 40 days, starting today (17th Feb). Now, a lot of people I know workout/run pretty much every day and could do this without giving it any real thought, but I am not one of them! So, as easy as this is for some, it will certainly be a test for me. 

Weekdays, workdays, rainy days, you name it, I’ll do it. Most probably quite begrudgingly! But that’s the whole point of a challenge I guess! So, if you can spare anything at all, please donate and I can lose some lbs whilst we make some £‘S... My puns will not improve with this challenge. 

Thank you,

S.

story:
#LateLentChallange2021

Hi, my friends, it is that time of the year that I used too took a bit of my time to make an effort to support Great Ormond Street Hospital. 

Who knows me understand how important it is for me to give back a bit to that amazing place. Hope you help me to Help them to keep bringing smiles back to families and their children.

Unfortunately this year due to a recent recovery from COVID-19 infection I'm not physically prepared yet to make it happen now.

 However, I will use this 40 days to get fit and after eater complete a Lete Lent Challange. 

During these 40 days, I will run every day to fundraise for them. Any kind of contribution will be welcome.

---

Olá meus amigos, chegou novamente aquele tempo do ano en que eu dedico um pouco do meu tempo para ajudar o Hospital Infantil Great Ormond Street. Quem me conheçe compreende o quão importante é para mim retribuir um pouco a este maravilhoso lugar. 

Espero que você possam me e ajudar a ajuda-los a continuar devolvendo sorrisos a crianças e seus familiares. 

Infelizmente devido a minha recente recuperação do COVID-19 não estou fisicamente preparado para isto, porem durante este período eu irei me preparar para logo após a pascoa completar este desafio.

Durante estes 40 dias, vou correr todos os dias para levantar fundos para o Hospital Infantil Great Ormond Street, qualquer contribuição é bem vinda.

You can follow it on my Instagram @bperez_br

eventName: ICI 2021 Team Charity Get Fit Challenge
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit ICI’s JustGiving page.

A couple of family members have benefitted from GOSH’s medical staff, care and treatments. At the age of two, it took eight months for Maia to be diagnosed with juvenile idiopathic arthritis (“JIA”). After two MRIs, numerous tests, X-Rays and three different hospitals, GOSH diagnosed her immediately and within less than a couple of weeks treated her with steroid injections in three joints (both knees and her right ankle) which allowed her to move freely and gave her such a boost of energy after her being lethargic and limited in movement for those first eight months. Two years later, GOSH treated her again in just one joint and fingers crossed she’s remained in remission ever since. Manuela,, was diagnosed with Raynaud’s condition* by GOSH and they’ve given her an effective treatment plan.

*Raynaud's (ray-NOSE) disease causes some areas of your body — such as your fingers and toes — to feel numb and cold in response to cold temperatures or stress. In Raynaud's disease, smaller arteries that supply blood to your skin become narrow, limiting blood flow to affected areas (vasospasm).

Over 600 children arrive at GOSH for treatment from all over the UK. On an average day at GOSH, 30 children have operations, helping to treat highly complex medical conditions. You’ll find 931 pioneering research projects rigorously seeking answers to the world’s rarest and most complex diseases. During the pandemic, GOSH has also adapted to treat COVID-19 patients particularly those of a younger generation.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. 

I have known lots of people whose lives have been affected by cancer. People dear to me have lost loved ones, close friends have fought and both won and lost their battle. This year Cancer stepped further into my life by touching someone in my family. 

I have been creating small craft pieces during lockdown down for fun and creativity purposes and sending them out as kindness gifts. People always ask if they can pay or if I have an online shop. The answer is, I don’t want to make money from them. At least, not for me. But if you feel that you can donate to my chosen charity instead then that would be paying the kindness forward in the most beautiful way! 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.


Thank you all! 

Keep on #KeepingItKind

All my love

Cate

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Hello All!

This year we have decided to take on the Marie Curie Thirteen Tors Challenge in Dartmoor to raise money for this wonderful charity. As a group we have all had experience of watching someone go through a terminal illness and end of life care and know just how important those last few moments are! Providing care and support to anyone going through difficult times (directly or indirectly) is something close to all our hearts. 

I do hope you will consider donating to this page to help us reach our fundraising goals and provide the care and support needed by many ❤

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
The Rotary Club of Bradford Blaize usually undertakes a collection in March at a local supermarket for theThe Marie Curie Bradford Hospice Great Daffodil Appeal. We are unable to do this in 2021 and so in it's place Robert Allan is aiming to walk 310,000 steps in March (10,00 a day) to raise money.

The Hospice supports people living with a terminal illness and those closest to them to live as well as possible. It is often very different place from what people expect - it is a warm, friendly space with beautiful gardens, delicious home-cooked food and personalised care. Every person is treated as an individual and helped to reach their goals and fulfil their wishes. A team of nurses, doctors, social workers, physiotherapists, chaplains, bereavement counsellors and pharmacists work together, putting every person at the centre of their care. Throughout Covid-19 Bradford Hospice teams have been working around the clock to continue supporting local people. Death, dying and bereavement is at the forefront of peoples minds and Marie Curie knows what a difference the right care at the end of life can make. They cant do any of this without your support. Thank you for your generous donation which supports the Bradford Hospice and Marie Curie care

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story: We have each been personally affected in our own lives by a serious or terminal illness but most recently, as a team, we sadly lost a colleague and a dear friend to Cancer. Nicky was taken far too soon and we would like to keep her memory alive by doing our bit, however big or small, to help the charities who give back to those who so desperately need support. Nicky would want us to remember her as the positive person that she was and she would always encourage us to get away from our desks and walk out in the fresh air so we are doing this in her honour! Thank you for your support:)

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
March will mark the 1 year anniversary since the loss of our beautiful and courageous friend Louise. Having being diagnosed and battling breast cancer myself I have decided to participate in Step into Spring in memory of lou and to raise money more Marie Curie who supported Louise and her family in her final weeks.
Throughout March myself, my mom, my partner and my best friend have pledged to walk 10,000 steps a day in memory of our friend and to "Walk all over Breast Cancer".

As many of you know I am also fighting my own personal Breast Cancer battle and I am still undergoing chemotherapy which is due to finish at the end of March. So I am taking on this challange to show my support for anyone battling this awful disease and to raise money for the people that are there every step of the way.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story: My friend Hazel and I are walking 100km in March to raise money for the wonderful Marie Curie Nurses. They have continued to give their incredible care all throughout the COVID pandemic, to people who are sadly at the end of their lives. This means that people have been cared for at home in line with their wishes, and also that family members have had the chance to get some much needed rest. It costs £20 an hour for a Marie Curie Nurse to care for someone at home, and we're raising £180 to pay for a night of care for patients and families who desperately need it. I'm so grateful for every donation, no matter how small. Thank you for all your support.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
March is a tough month for us all after the tragic loss of our beautiful friend Lou. Our beloved Lou lost her battle on 5th March 2020 and this year will mark the first year without her, the 24th March is Lous 40th Birthday where she should be here to celebrate. Together we will be challenging ourselves to walking 10.000 steps a day throughout the whole of March to honour Lous memory & to raise money for the amazing Marie Curie where Lou spent her final weeks.

Lou, March is all about you🌼💛

Jemma, Steph, Chelsea, Jobbo & Alex

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Our Solihull Hospice has been caring for local people since 1965.

Its a warm and welcoming place where we give expert care to people with a terminal illness, and their loved ones, every day of the year. 

Our hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by over 200 volunteers  who play a vital role in the running of the hospice.

We have a 24-bed in-patient unit, where relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish.

Our out-patient unit offers clinics, therapies and group sessions  and freshly cooked lunches made by our chefs. We also support carers and families, including children, with practical advice, counselling and bereavement support groups.

We need to raise £9,600 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Solihull get the care and support they need.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
This March, Morrisons and Marie Curie are working side by side to raise vital funds for frontline nurses to help dying people and their loved ones.

This has been a hard year for everyone. Weve faced challenging times as a nation, and we know it's the small moments that bring people together. Such moments can be made possible for dying people and their loved ones by the expert care of Marie Curie Nurses, who can bring care, comfort and clarity at the very toughest time. 

Your support means the world to people affected by terminal illness.  From picking your daffodil in-store and wearing it with pride, to taking on your own fundraising challenge you're making vital care possible.

Put simply, without the support people like you highly skilled Marie Curie Nurses couldn't continue giving vital care to people living with a terminal illness and their families.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
I am taking part in the Cornwall RNLI virtual challenge 2021 to help support the RNLI's volunteer crews in saving lives around our coast. 

The Challenge is to complete a Run, Walk, Cycle, or Swim over the period between 1st February to 31st March. The distance can be between two or more Cornish Lifeboat Stations, picking the distance that best suits and it can be carried out anywhere, be that a garden, park, swimming pool or even a treadmill.

There are a total of 13 RNLI lifeboat stations around the coast of Cornwall, from Bude to Looe with the total overall distance is 228 miles.

Bude to Port Isaac = 30 miles
Port Isaac to Rock = 9 miles
Rock to Padstow  17 miles
Padstow to Newquay = 15 miles
Newquay to St Agnes = 13 miles
St Agnes to St Ives = 21 miles
St Ives to Sennen = 17 miles
Sennen to Penlee = 8 miles
Penlee to Lizard = 25 miles
Lizard to Falmouth = 21 miles
Falmouth to Fowey = 33 miles
Fowey to Looe = 19 miles

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
eventName: Coastal Convoy - In Aid Of The RNLI
story:
We are hosting a convoy along the coasts of Europe in aid of the RNLI. The RNLI is a service in the UK and Ireland protecting our shores, and keeping the people who use it safe. They are made up of 95% volunteers, putting their lives on hold to help others out at sea, at a moments notice. They rely fully on donations from the members of the public in order to keep going.

We'll have three routes, along the coast, in aid of the RNLI. You can find out all of the information you need to know in our discord server, and down below. There will be prizes on offer for the truckfest, but that will be announced later on.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
As many of you know I have done a few daft things to raise money for charity over the past years and skydiving will remain my favourite but falling with style doesn't require much effort so...

This challenge is requires slightly more effort, commencing on the 5th of March at 0400 I will run 4 miles every 4 hours for 48 hours which means in 2 days I will run almost 2 marathons.

Last year Kinghorn RNLI crew's were paged nearly 100 times making it one of busiest years in a while. As operational crew it means that we need to drop everything when the pagers go off and sadly I miss some work meetings (all sarcasm intended).

Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Guys: I've made a ghastly error. Back in January, when late February seemed many moons away, I signed up for a charity run: to run 20 miles (YES GUYS TWENTY) in 20 hours, one mile each hour, to challenge myself and raise money for the good work that WWF do. And then I forgot.


It transpires that this weekend is that weekend. Starting from 4am on Saturday morning (SHUDDER), I'll run a mile each hour for 20 hours. I shall hate it. The forecast says rain. I won't get any sleep until almost a full day later. I shall complain.

I have a modest fundraising target of £100, so if you can bear (BEAR, WWF, geddit) to lob me a fiver and help the charity that cares about ocean plastic, climate change and snow leopards, then I'll be forever grateful. 

________

Nature needs us. Every second, every minute, every hour. I'm making the most of my time and reaching my potential to do as much as I can for my health and nature. I'm running one mile every hour, maximising the time in-between to raise money to fight for our world.

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
story:
We are sad to announce the passing of our beloved grandmother. A lady never short of a joke, a poem, or a freestyle song. She went by a few names Kay, Kiki, Kyriacou, Giggs, and was loved by all.

Kay was born in Eptakomi, a place she had cherished memories of as a young girl. She continually told stories of the days when she was a child and wrote many wonderful poems about Cyprus. She travelled to London at the age of 18 to visit the Queen and then planned to return to her beloved village in Cyprus however she was not expecting to meet the love of her life Harry, who she was married to for 52 happy years. They owned the Cabin Cafe in Tottenham for 37 years working together where she felt happiest; cooking. After retiring Kay volunteered to work at Oxfam in Palmers Green. She made lots of friends there and it kept her busy since she loved to talk and meet new people and she really enjoyed helping out. Harry would walk up to Palmers Green and pick her up once she finished work and they would then walk home together before popping into Morrisons for a cup of tea. Kay loved to tell stories, write poetry and have friends and family surrounding her. She was the kindest, most generous lady who was so witty and always put everyone else's needs before her own. Kay will be sorely missed, she will always be in our hearts and she has now gone to join her beloved Harry.

Oxfam is a charity our grandmother held close to her heart and we know she would be grateful for all donations made. If you prefer to provide a donation in a different form this will also be warmly received. 

Thank you,

Kay’s grandchildren xx

eventName: SANNE Corporate Challenge 2021 - From Tokyo to New York
story:
SANNE will be taking a virtual journey across the globe in 30 days, travelling from our offices in Tokyo to New York.

The objective of the initiative is to collectively travel the distance of 10,800km (the distance between Tokyo and NY) within 30 days while fundraising for UNICEF. 

Sanne are a global team with 1800+ employees in 20 different locations. The initiative is designed to take a virtual journey across the globe through the eyes of our colleagues by sharing selfies, maps and pictures of the locations travelled over the 30 days so we can view the world from a different perspective. Each participants distance contributes towards the total for the group and progresses the entire group along the virtual journey. 

UNICEF, also known as the United Nations International Children's Emergency Fund, is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. The agency is among the most widespread and recognizable social welfare organizations in the world, with a presence in 192 countries and territories. UNICEF's activities include providing immunizations and disease prevention, administering treatment for children and mothers with HIV, enhancing childhood and maternal nutrition, improving sanitation, promoting education, and providing emergency relief in response to disasters. 

The charity has been chosen to align with four of our CSR initiatives: 

- Supporting initiatives that help benefit and improve the lives of children 

- Supporting initiatives that help in the fight against poverty 

- Supporting initiatives that give people a better education and start in life 

- Supporting initiatives that promote health and wellbeing.

story:
All donations made on this page will go to Médecins Sans Frontières UK. 

An international, independent medical humanitarian organisation. Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF) translates to Doctors without Borders. We provide medical assistance to people affected by conflict, epidemics, disasters, or exclusion from healthcare. 

MSF teams and facilities supported by MSF have treated more than 80,000 patients wounded by violence across 12 governorates since the conflict began in March 2015. According to the Yemen Data Project, more than 22,000 air raids had been recorded by November 2020.

charity.description: Malaria No More UK mobilises governments, influencers, businesses and the public to end deaths from malaria and wipe out the disease for good. Our mission is to catalyse and inspire the global partnerships, leadership and financing to make malaria no more in a generation.
charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
story: In 2019 it is estimated that 409,000 people around the world died from malaria - a preventable disease - the majority being children under five and pregnant women (source: WHO). 2021 is a vital year in the global campaign to make our world one without malaria. This coming June, the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting and the vitally important Kigali Summit on malaria and neglected tropical diseases will take place in Rwanda. The summit marks a historic moment that will unite global leaders and put a spotlight on the importance of renewed action in fighting malaria. We need more action, more innovation, more funding and more political leadership to defeat malaria and move forward stronger in this new global health landscape. Across Rentokil Initial, colleagues are taking part in a 9,000km Race to Kigali (the distance between our HQ and Kigali, Rwanda), including teams from America, Australia, Asia, Europe, the Middle East, Caribbean, Africa, HR, IT, Finance, M&A and Legal. By combining the efforts of colleagues walking, running or cycling, each team will ‘reach’ the distance to Kigali. This is our global effort to raise funds and show our support for this vital cause. It all starts on Monday 15 February through to the UN’s World Malaria Day on 25 April. Andy Ransom: "As a proud patron of Malaria No More UK, I am asking my colleagues at Rentokil Initial, as well as friends, family and associates to get involved in the Race to Kigali. In doing so, helping raise incredibly important funding for Malaria No More UK at such a critical time. Rentokil Initial Cares, our charitable fund, will match every £1 raised up to £100,000.” Together we can achieve a Zero Malaria world within a generation. Please show your support.

charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

story:
During March I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.


My target is 8km a day but I am hoping to do more, subject to Covid restrictions.
